permanently confined to the home, does it? I'm pretty sure the &quot;lack of socialisation&quot; criticism is a non-starter for most &quot;home&quot; educated children. &#10;And let's not even mention, shall we, how most parents seem not to notice that the kind of &quot;socialisation&quot; practised in a typical school is more in the nature of imposed association than what most adults would regard as &quot;socialising&quot;. &#10;Added to that, the education issue is no longer about school vs not school, it's about the growth of online learning and the evolution of mobile technology and that means we're approaching a reality where nobody needs to be physically present in a school classroom in order to be educated. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="959" language="en" documentId="992" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="bobcollier" date="07 November 2009 2:46am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6751535" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="10" thumbsDown="0" origId="992" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="219"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="220" end="432"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="433" end="668"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="669" end="959"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>